text: EXPOSICI N EN EL MUSEO DE SAN JUAN DE LA MATAEl de julio de se ha inaugurado una nueva exposici n con el t tulo EL FUEGO EN EL PRADOHomenaje al Museo del Prado en su Bicentenario Complementa y ampl a la exposici n anterior sobre el mismo tema pero con obras pertenecientes al Museo del Prado Vel zquez Rubens Goya El Bosco Cossiers Y como plato fuerte Un cuadro viviente Santalla StrartS y QuinSan han creado la Asociaci n de Museos Virtuales cuyo fin es que todos los pueblos independientemente de su poblaci n puedan disponer de un museo de arte El lema es NING N PUEBLO SIN MUSEO EXHIBITION AT THE SAN JUAN DE LA MATA MUSEUMOn July a new exhibition with the title was inaugurated THE FIRE IN THE PRADOTribute to the Prado Museum in its BicentennialIt complements and extends the previous exhibition on the same subject but with works belonging to the Museo del Prado Vel zquez Rubens Goya El Bosco Cossiers And as a main course A living painting Santalla StrartS and QuinSan have created the Association of Virtual Museums whose goal is that all peoples regardless of their population can have an art museum The motto is NO PEOPLE WITHOUT MUSEUM museodelprado reinasofiamuseum caixaforum museothyssen hermitagemuseum whitneymuseum centrepompidou nationalgallery moma modernart museedorsay louvre met britishmuseum tatemodern guggenheim nycart brooklynmuseum lacmamuseum gemaldegalerie artinstitutechicago ufizzi louvreabudhabi yaleartgallery galleriaborghese gettymuseum sfmoma nationalgalleryofart altepinakothek rijksmuseum

text: Diario di viaggio day Risvegliarsi e trovare un infreddolito Andrea avvolto nel lenzuolo che decide di indossare un maglione in pile nonostante il caldo africano Fare colazione e pranzo a distanza di trenta minuti nello stesso posto Salire sulle mura del palazzo dell Alcazaba e constatare che la vista aerea di Malaga deludente quanto le sue spiagge tanto da farla somigliare a certi quartieri della periferia di Catania Perdersi nel labirintico palazzo che in realt era un semplice quadrato Salire a piedi sotto il sole cocente sul castillo de Gibralfaro passando per un ripidissimo sentiero in salita e dedurre che da queste parti ai tempi della costruzione della fortezza i sentieri a tornanti per diminuire la pendenza non erano stati ancora inventati Ricevere una scarpata per aver rivelato solo in cima al promontorio che in realt esisteva un autobus per la nostra meta Ammirare la citt dal punto pi panoramico circondati da alberi e scoiattoli ma non riuscire a scattare foto decenti a causa dei nuvoloni neri e della nebbia arrivati all improvviso da non si sa dove annunciatori di una imminente tempesta Discutere di macabri argomenti come accidentali cadute dalle mura del castello ed essere messi in guardia da Daniele che prontamente afferma che qualora uno di noi cadesse lui tirerebbe dritto facendo finta di niente Ridiscendere per il ripido e scivoloso sentiero sotto un rinnovato cocente sole e sentirsi morire alla vista di un corridore che marciava tranquillamente e a passo svelto nel senso opposto al nostro Passeggiare lungo il moderno porto turistico di Malaga Entrare al Centre Pompidou appendice di quello parigino per contemplare opere e installazioni di arte contemporanea e trovarle molto affascinanti Rientrare a Milano riflettendo su quanto non conti la bellezza dei posti che si visitano quando si con la giusta compagnia in grado di trasformare una semplice vacanza in una divertente avventura malaga alcazaba gibralfaro centrepompidou

name: 2019-09-18 22.56.36 2135697445925985690_centrepompidou.jpg
text: What are the conditions for mutual trust A Workshop on Trust Boundaries With Myriam Lefkowitz th th of September am pm at M ArthurBoskampStiftung The two day workshop is dedicated to the themes of trust and boundaries both in interpersonal relationships and in relation to the public space in which we move daily Especially when we take care of other people mutual trust plays an indispensable role However we also quickly lose ourselves in the process of caring for others and in doing so also lose the fine perception for ourselves and our environment How can these conditions for mutual trust be explored and how can we sensitize our perception of our environment and our personal boundaries The first part of the workshop will take place in M for the second part we will explore Hohenlockstedt with an experimental walk One workshop participant will silently guide another participant through town The guided person is asked to close his her eyes and only open them on instruction Walking together enhances the sensory experience and transfers the familiar perception of the place to the entire body Through the touch of being led the conditions for mutual trust and the feeling of one s own limits are explored and negotiated non verbally The French American performance artist MyriamLefkowitz who lives in Paris investigates the close connections between perception and imagination in order to create conditions for extended sensory experiences These concerns also shape her ongoing project WALK HANDS EYES HOHENLOCKSTEDT Her works have been presented at the VeniceBiennale the KadistFoundation San Fransisco the MOT Tokyo DeApple Amsterdam the LeNouveauFestival CentrePompidou the BergenTriennale and at the FermeduBuisson Paris She teaches regularly at SciencePo Paris OpenSchoolEast London the RoyalInstituteofArt Stockholm DasArt Amsterdam and others In it was awarded by IF I CAN T DANCEI DON T WANT TO BE PART OF YOUR REVOLUTION Amsterdam and is currently an associated artist at Ferme du Buisson

text: ST PHANE MANDELBAUM Le Mus e Juif de Belgique dresse le portrait d une figure atypique de l histoire de l art belge dans une r trospective blouissante St phane Mandelbaum na t Bruxelles en Ses parents sont tous deux artistes et le jeune St phane montre tr s vite des dispositions exceptionnelles pour le dessin Souffrant de dyslexie s v re il est envoy dans une cole La Louvi re Les dessins fleurissent dans les marges de ses feuilles de cours et son amour pour l art le conduira l Acad mie de Watermael Boitsfort et l cole des Arts d Uccle o il s initiera la gravure Il nourrit principalement sa cr ation des grandes figures de la transgression et de la violence Cette curieuse admiration le m nera tre m l diverses affaires dont le vol dans un appartement de l Avenue Louise d un tableau de Modigliani en Ce vol lui sera fatal Il est assassin par ses complices et abandonn dans un terrain vague de la banlieue de Namur L uvre de Stephane Mandelbaum est compulsive et empreinte de violence Il tire principalement son inspiration de ses racines juives et de figures tourment es Rimbaud Bacon coupdec urApr s le Centre Pompidou de Paris la r trospective ST PHANE MANDELBAUM est encore visible au Mus e Juif de Belgique jusqu ce dimanche septembre Pour plus d informations www mjb jmb org stephane mandelbaum juin au septembre

text: NIKOLAI SUETIN BIOGRAPHY PHOTOS have heard of Suetin Daily poll Suetin arrives in revolutionary VITEBSK now belarus as a REDARMY soldier In his leisure time he joins the People s Free Art College Malevich arrives as a teacher at the College and Nikolai becomes a follower of Malevich and his Suprematism Abstract art with geometric forms and colour SUPREMATIST DESIGN in London in and part of the Sepherot collection COMPOSITION Suetin is a founder member of UNOVIS Champions of the New Art They are committed to developing the new art for the new world They paint and transform the town of Vitebsk Long live workers power street design Long live the revolution design for tram Malevich Suetin and others leave for Petrograd Now SaintPetersburg russia Suetintakes on various design roles including porcelain from at the State Porcelain factory They work at GINKhUK Museum of Artistic Culture as a laboratory developing experiments on innovative models for the future world of plenty no wars and full equality Collage c In GINKHUK is attacked in Leningrad Pravda as a monastery that does not deserve state funding This happens as the ruling state bureaucracy strengthen their power under Stalin GINKhUK is closed and state funding options are reduced and limited ONWARDS With Stalin s power assured the old ways of life return Malevich and Suetin returned to painting and much more They combine Suprematism with figuration in an innovative way After Stalin s crackdown on radical culture accelerates in the s Suetin survives and thrives in developing Soviet design for Porcelain World Fairs Museums He is awarded the Order of Lenin in His Suprematist influences are hidden in traditional forms at centrepompidou paris costakis collection in Thessaloniki current on show at the scottishnationalgallery in edinburgh as part of the collage exhibition sothebys geometricalart

text: Just got back from a trip to Keble College Oxford where my uncle Vitit Muntarbhorn KBE was selected to be part of an exhibition Portrait of Keble which marks the beginning of the th anniversary of the college In Vitit Muntarbhorn was selected as the first UN Expert to protect LGBTQ against violence and discrimination setting a clear mandate to decriminalise same sex relations globally And with his previous positions as the UN Special Rapporteur on Human Rights in North Korea and as a member of UN Commissions of Inquiry covering Syria and the Ivory Coast he was knighted for his contribution to International Human Rights in individuals were selected from years of co education at Keble for their inspirational achievements be they personal professional or both My heart is filled with gratitude to attend this event Dreams really do come true WatchTheMuntarbhorns

text: Fancy eating a Kandinsky Here is Yellow Red Blue A cake I designed and made for lovers of art The brief was to set about designing a wedding cake not like the norm and so I designed a cake to be viewed from above to reveal one of their favourite paintings It took on many forms from differing angles as you looked through the D cake shapes but the birdseye view revealed the amazing Kandinsky artwork The cake was covered in massa ticino sugarpaste saracinouk modelling paste and tempered isomalt squireskitchen was used to create the D elements Thank you goes out to thecakeriebridgend for millions of help with baking and covering and Sharon for my isomalt lesson and borrowing of stuff and of course the bride and groom Lisa and Jeff for asking me as it was a privilege kandinsky wassilykandinsky kandinskyinspired guggenheim guggenheimmuseum tatemodern lenbachhaus lenbachhausm nchen centrepompidou cakedecoratingmagazine cakemasters cake edibleart squireskitchen fondant massa ticino sugarpaste art weddingcakes mrbakerscakes

text: Paris Today is my birthday Well fellow followers you are seeing this colourful shot of Beaubourg and now let s dive in This is Centre Pompidou or Beaubourg it contains over works of art including paintings sculpture drawings and photography At first Beaubourg was commissioned to provide a cultural centre focused on and championing only all modern artNow its fa ade its multicolour fa ade is a subject of much debate in Paris and many French people didn t and still don t like the appearance of the building and compare it to a boiler house or an oil refinery Do you have the same feeling of it Leave a comment in the comment section below My website www frozensailor com Check it out beaubourg architecturegames travelinbetween huffposttravel iwalkedthisstreet arkitekt centrepompidou onlyinparis architecturegames parisfrance paristourisme frozensailor athomeintheworld sidewalkerdaily finearchitecture expobacon beautifulparis youngarchitect allshots goopgo wheretofindme parisobviously postcardplaces lecentrepompidouvuparvous artmoderne parisians

text: Mesmerized by the art of Brancusi Br ncu i was a Romanian sculptor painter and photographer He lived most of his life in France at his death Br ncu i left photographs and sculptures He bequeathed part of his collection to the French state on condition that his workshop be rebuilt as it was on the day he died This reconstruction of his studio adjacent to the Pompidou Centre is open to the public Considered a pioneer of modernism one of the most influential sculptors of the th century Br ncu i is called the patriarch of modernsculpture

name: 2019-09-23 06.02.12 2138810757633491267_centrepompidou.jpg
text: Portraits of the Duke and Duchess of Urbino by Piero della Francesca in Uffizi Gallery Florence Italy One of the most celebrated portraits of the Italian Renaissance the diptych features the Duke of Urbino Federico da Montefeltro and his wife Battista Sforza In the tradition of the fourteenth century inspired by the design of ancient coins the two figures are shown in profile an angle that ensured a good likeness and a faithful representation of facial details without allowing their sentiments to show through indeed the Duke and Duchess of Urbino appear unaffected by turmoil and emotions The couple are facing each other and the spatial element is suggested by the light and the continuity of the rolling landscape in the background representing the area of the Marches over which the Duke and Duchess ruled The chromatic contrast between the bronze skin tones used for Federico and the pale tones of Battista Sforza is striking the pale pallor of the Duchess not only respects the aesthetic conventions which were fashionable during the Renaissance but could also allude to her untimely death in The presence of the images on the reverse side suggests that the two paintings now set in a modern frame would once have been part of a diptych One of the Piero della Francesca s most famous works the double portrait is representative of the relationship between the painter and the Duke and Duchess of Montefeltro Piero was a frequent guest at their court finding himself in a cultured and refined atmosphere which would soon become one of the most important cultural and artistic hearts of Italy The master painter marries the strict approach to perspective learned during his Florentine education with the lenticular representation more characteristic of Flemish painting achieving extraordinary results and unmatched originality tbt portraitsofthedukeanddutchessofurbino pierodellafrancesca uffizigallery florence italy centrepompidou paris france art text: EARLY BIRD ends today AAA presents the last in a series of architectural talks Iconic Buildings of the th Century CENTRE POMPIDOU So everyone knows the Centre Pompidou colloquially known as Beaubourg right Wrong and more than most could believe It is the most visited building in Paris in a city that boasts the Louvre the Musee d Orsay and the Musee du Quai Branly In fact it is the most popular museum in the world Come and hear the background to this extraordinary building that will give you a completely different perspective on this great site and what many believe is a turning point in Modernism Be enthralled as Tone Wheeler architect and President of the AAA gives his third talk in which we go back to the competition Tone has a copy of the original brief and look at the ideas of the time revealing the story of how the Centre Pompidou was conceived and executed Talk DetailsDate Thursday th September pm pmLocation Brickworks Design Studio Barrack St SydneyEvent cost earlybird closes Monday rd Sep public AAA Members booking fee Eventbrite Tickets Link via website in bio Drinks and Canapes will be served from pm Presentation commences at pm ausarchitecture centrepompidou

text: Photos from my visit to Constantin Br ncu i s atelier in Paris At the end of his life Br ncu i stopped making new work focusing instead on the spatial relationship of the many sculptures within his studio arranging and rearranging them into mobile groups until he was satisfied with their orientation Br ncu i bequeathed his entire studio to the French state in on the condition that they must reconstruct it in its original state His atelier is free and open to the public located opposite the incredible CentrePompidou and a couple blocks from my favorite restaurant GrandC ur grandcoeur restaurant

text: Jewish art dealer Paul Rosenberg played a pivotal role not only in the Parisian gallery scene of the first half of the th century but was widely acknowledged to be the most active and influential gallerist in the world Anticipating the effects of a Nazi occupation he was able to start moving his collection out of Paris in the s loaning works to international exhibition and storing others in a bank vault in the south of France He was labeled a degenerate and though he was able to escape further Nazi persecution by escaping France his remaining collection of over works by modern masters like Picasso Matisse and Leger were seized by the Germans with many pieces ending up in the collections of high level Nazi generals When the Allies closed in on Paris in the Nazis loaded most of Rosenberg s works onto a train leaving the city The cargo however would be hijacked and saved by members of the FreeFrenchArmy including Rosenberg s son After the war Rosenberg worked tirelessly to reassemble the collection Of missing paintings he was able to retrieve over nazilootedart paris gallery modernmasters arthistory themoreyouknow arteducation artadvice artstories centrepompidou paulrosenberg acqr acquireart

text: VASARELY SHARING FORMS centrepompidou February May Vaserely Sharing Forms is the first major exhibition devoted to Victor Vasarely for more than half a century Known as the inventor of optical kinetic art he significantly revolutionised geometric abstraction This exhibit provides a chronological thematic overview of an opus that was driven by the conviction that art can change life provided it radically changes its mode of conception production dissemination Between science fiction the cosmos the fourth dimension provided the framework for the formal effervescence of Vasarely s later work The major series produced in the s s Vega Vonal Tridim CTA share the cosmic imagery of science fiction They are inspired by a radiating multidimensional breathing cosmos Centre Pompidou The Vega series exhibit grids that shift expand forming enormous bubbles at their surface stretching their forms causing the light to flow over its rounded contour According to Vasarely the wave that hollows out or puffs up the grid manages to convey the way in which matter energy deforms space Vega Tek Vega Zett victorvasarely centrepompidou parisartexhibition opticalkineticart opticalillusion cosmicimagery vegazett vasarelyart springinparis vasarelyexhibition victorvasarelyart victorvasarelyexhibition vasarelysharingforms geometricabstraction multidimensionalimages artmovement opart contemporaryart paris france

text: centrepompidou In memory of george dyer Central part Bacon met Dyer in Their relationship was tumultuous and ultimately tragic with Dyer passing away in two nights before the opening of Bacon s retrospective at the Grand Palais Paris Bacon painted portraits of Dyer obsessively both during their relationship and after Dyer s death This piece marks the start of Bacon s black triptych phase Bacon s grief inspired some of his most emotive works during this time including Triptych August and Triptych May June which confronted the moment of Dyer s death And even though he was not always named Dyer continued to appear in numerous paintings throughout Bacon s career centrepompidou francisbacon bacon crucifixionbacon contemporarypainter wladimirautain

text: VASARELY SHARING FORMS centrepompidou February May Victor Vaserely developed a plastic alphabet in the early s consisting of a lexicon of single geometrical forms embedded in a system of pure color The artist aimed to create a visual and universal language whose combined properties render it suitable to all adaptations Since each of the pure colors of the plastic alphabet generated to intermediary chromatic values the lightness or darkness of color In order to master the many combinatory possibilities of this alphabet Vaserely attributed letters to his forms and numbers to his colors and expressed them within a systematic and programmable set of permutations and progressions that could be written on a sheet of graph paper Majus acrylic on canvas is one of the most remarkable works to result from the plastic alphabet Grand Iboya Talia towers Pyr Fekete pyramid are made with Luran acrylic elements pasted on wood victorvaserely centrepompidou parisartexhibition opart opticalkineticart opticalillusion artmovement geometricabstraction plasticalphabet visuallanguage universallanguage chromaticvaluescale grandiboya vasarelyart springinparis vasarelyexhibition multidimensionalimages contemporaryart paris france

text: The stunning and moving Francis Bacon painting Three Portraits Posthumous Portrait of George Dyer Self Portrait Portrait of Lycian Freud is on view at the Pompidou in the extraordinary Francis Bacon Books and Paintings exhibition The show focuses on works produced by Bacon in the last two decades of his career post Popes and places literature at the heart of the exhibition Whilst always denying any narrative in his work Bacon nevertheless admitted literature represented a powerful stimulus for his imagination Though it is purely a paintings show many of these works were the catalyst and inspiration for his stunning original lithographs francisbacon centrepompidou paintings paris triptych literature inspiration postpopes portraiture

text: B A C O NSince I was about yrs old I have been fascinated by the British Irish artist Francis Bacon I was introduced to him by my art teacher at school as I was and still am in love with Brett Whiteley she got me to look at his influences Bacon was the most obvious and strong for me Bacon s paintings show his absolute mastery of balance Balance between control and chaos violence and peace space and contortion beauty and death I have been lucky enough to see two exhibitions of Bacon one in Sydney and now this stunning one in Paris francisbacon centrepompidou abstractart fineart red artexhibition teeth mouth abstraction figurativepainting raw

text: centrepompidou Second Version of Triptych right part Early successBy Bacon had gained confidence His Three Studies for Figures at the Base of a Crucifixion had summarised themes explored in his earlier paintings including his examination of Picasso s biomorphs his interpretations of the Crucifixion and the Greek Furies It is generally considered his first mature piece He regarded his works before the triptych as irrelevant The painting caused a sensation when exhibited in and established him as a foremost post war painter centrepompidou francisbacon bacon crucifixionbacon contemporarypainter wladimirautain

text: SavetheDate michel nedjar an anthology of French art galeristes oct at lecarreaudutemple Michel Nedjar s extraordinary trajectory raises a question that is rarely addressed the possible impermanence of Art Brut Jean Dubuffet wrote to him of his admiration on numerous occasions and the addition of his work to his Art Brut collection was accompanied by a text by the great English critic Roger Cardinal while many dozens of his pieces appear today in the centrepompidou s collections Discovered almost years ago today he is without a doubt the living Brut artist who has been the most exposed worldwide and who has been the subject of a great number of publications We ll announce the other artists soon japon brut the moon the sun yamanami until october visit the link in our bio to see further info

text: El rollo blanco y negro me lo guard para Paris En mi habit culo emocional yo esperaba que esta semana fuera como si la dirigiese Jean Luc Gordard o por qu no Fran ois Truffaut all por la d cada del As como salida de un film de la Nouvelle Vague mi paso por esta hermosa ciudad fue un canto a la plenitud de la vida un deseo de libertad y un reconocimiento de la adultez desde la optica de mi espiritu joven Esta ciudad llena de frescura y autenticidad narra historias Congelando el tiempo me llev a la b squeda de sensaciones en todos sitios y momentos En esta ciudad se confunde el pasado con el presente la realidad con la ilusi n y la f bula nace de la experiencia que la imaginaci n trasciende Gracias Paris por tanta magia I was keeping the black and white film specially for Paris Deep in my emotions I was hoping this week to be as if Jean Luc Godard directed it or why not Fran ois Truffaut back then in the s Just like a film from the Nouvelle Vague movement my experience in this beautiful city was an ode to the plenitude of life a wish for liberty and an acknowledgement to adulthood from the perspective of my young spirit This city is full of freshness authenticity and it tells stories Freezing the time it lead me to the searching of new sensations in every place and moment In this city the past is mistaken with the present and reality with illusion The fable is born from the experience that transcends imagination Thank you Paris for such magic Developed by yarkiy ru mmfilm mmphotography olympus olympusoz r analogphotography analog analogic film filmisnotdead filmphotography filmcommunity photography analogica filmcommunity films filmography mm paris france blackandwhite city versailles toureiffel centrepompidou photo photography
